@edition "2026.6"

-- D1(xix) frontier guardrail. This program is VALID (it type-checks clean — a `_test`,
-- not a `_bad`), but it uses a `loop` (an unbounded imperative loop exited by `break`).
-- eval runs the body repeatedly, mutating the `mut` counter/accumulator, until a `break`
-- escapes; the loop is Unit-typed and the result comes from the accumulator read after it.
-- The compute spine has no loop lowering — `tail`/`block` reach the `Loop` AST node (and
-- `break`/`continue` are their own nodes) and refuse it. The differential harness must
-- report it `unsupported` — a CLEAN refusal at the compiler frontier, never a miscompile.
--
-- This is the backend-slice analogue of a `_bad` twin: a backend slice adds no checker
-- rejection rule, so the guarantee under test is "the compiler refuses what it cannot
-- yet lower, loudly", asserted by the harness rather than by an error count. D1(ii)
-- moved the frontier PAST scalar `match`; D1(iii) PAST tuples; D1(iv) PAST ADT
-- constructors; D1(v) PAST records; D1(vi) PAST lists; D1(vii) PAST closures-as-values;
-- D1(viii) PAST first-class `def` references; D1(ix) PAST first-class BUILTIN references;
-- D1(x) PAST short-circuit `&&`/`||`; D1(xi) PAST non-tail `if` as a value; D1(xii) PAST
-- non-tail `match` as a value; D1(xiii) PAST multi-clause `def`s; D1(xiv) PAST reassignment;
-- D1(xv) PAST atom literals; D1(xvi) PAST duration literals; D1(xvii) PAST `for`
-- comprehensions; D1(xviii) PAST integer ranges; D1(xix) PAST INDEX ASSIGNMENT (`xs[i] = v`,
-- an in-place list-element write; see compile_assign_test). The frontier now sits at the
-- `loop` construct. This file uses one, so it still refuses; when loops lower (a later D1
-- slice, a JS `while (true)` with `break`/`continue`), it flips from `unsupported` to a print
-- with no edit.

def sumTo(n: Number): Number
  mut i = 0
  mut total = 0
  loop
    if i >= n
      break
    total = total + i
    i = i + 1
  total

def main(): Effect [io] ()
  println(sumTo(5))
